        </mj-text>
        <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.longandshort.com/email/images/ls-jan-28-3.png" alt="What is hyperbolic discounting in behavioral finance?" href="https://www.longandshort.com" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000"> 
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">Hyperbolic discounting is a behavioral finance concept that explains why individuals prefer smaller immediate rewards instead of larger ones in the distant future. It shows that people disproportionately value rewards in the short term over those in the future.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">
          Given a choice between receiving $50 today or $100 in a year, many people opt for the immediate $50 even though waiting offers a higher return. This bias often leads to impulsive decisions such as overspending or under-saving for retirement.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">Hyperbolic discounting can also explain behaviors like procrastination or overusing credit cards. Understanding this bias is crucial for financial planning.
         </p>
        </mj-text>
